<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-09T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-09T05:00:00-05:00" n="435" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d435">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">868.51 War Credits/654:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-09T12:00:00+02:00">March 9,
                                    1934—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 9—11:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>26. Your 16, March 7, 8 p.m. The Foreign Minister told me last night
                                that the Greek Government had not yet issued the instructions
                                referred to but had on March 7 addressed a letter to the
                                International Financial Commission requesting permission to do so at
                                once exempting payments to such creditors as still insist on
                                payments on gold basis. This morning he requested me to inform you
                                that the United States 1929 loan will be given equal treatment under
                                the same reservations as last year.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>